sed","1245–Male":"1245–Deceased","1248–Female":"1248–Deceased","1267–1317":"1267–1317","1228–1265":"1228–1265","1225–1279":"1225–1279","1228":"1228","1248":"1248","1225":"1225","1279":"1279","1245":"1245","1267":"1267","1265":"1265","about 1267":"about 1267","1317":"1317","Peckleton, Leicestershire, England":"Peckleton, Leicestershire, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Moton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Mutton  .","Probably also an altered form of English   Morton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Mutton","meanings":["English (Cornwall and Northamptonshire):","nickname from Middle English <i>motoun</i> ‘sheep’ (Old French <i>mouton</i>).","variant of   Mitton  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Moton was born in 1245, in England, United Kingdom, his father, Robert Moton, was 17 and his mother, Sarah, was 20. He had at least 1 son with Sarah."},"et":{"1245–":"1245–Surnud","1245–Male":"1245–Surnud","1248–Female":"1248–Surnud","1267–1317":"1267–1317","1228–1265":"1228–1265","1225–1279":"1225–1279","1228":"1228","1248":"1248","1225":"1225","1279":"1279","1245":"1245","1267":"1267","1265":"1265","about 1267":"umbes 1267","1317":"1317","Peckleton, Leicestershire, England":"Peckleton, Leicestershire, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1245–":"1245–Kuollut","1245–Male":"1245–Kuollut","1248–Female":"1248–Kuollut","1267–1317":"1267–1317","1228–1265":"1228–1265","1225–1279":"1225–1279","1228":"1228","1248":"1248","1225":"1225","1279":"1279","1245":"1245","1267":"1267","1265":"1265","about 1267":"noin 1267","1317":"1317","Peckleton, Leicestershire, England":"Peckleton, Leicestershire, England","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1245–":"1245–Décédé","1245–Male":"1245–Décédé","1248–Female":"1248–Décédée","1267–1317":"1267–1317","1228–1265":"1228–1265","1225–1279":"1225–1279","1228":"1228","1248":"1248","1225":"1225","1279":"1279","1245":"1245","1267":"1267","1265":"1265","about 1267":"environ 1267","1317":"1317","Peckleton, Leicestershire, England":"Peckleton, Leicestershire, Angleterre","England":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Robert de Moton est né en 1245, à Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, son p